outlooksByWeek.1: Saquon Barkley stays in the NFC East with a move from the bumbling Giants to Super Bowl contender Philadelphia.  Barkley was injury-prone during his time with the G-Men, but still maintained his explosiveness when healthy, and should benefit from a bevy of weapons around him on the Eagles, rather than being the sole focal point of a mediocre offense as he was in New York.  In Week 1, Barkley will have an extremely favorable matchup versus a  Packers defense that allowed 128.3 rushing yards per tilt in 2023, which was 28th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Saquon Barkley had a debut for the ages for the Philadelphia Eagles.  Barkley racked up 132 scrimmage yards and three total touchdowns in the season-opening victory over the Packers.  Barkley flashed explosiveness both as a runner and pass-catcher, including a nifty touchdown reception on a wheel route out of the backfield.  Barkley had 26 touches in Week 1, and should continue to command a heavy workload in Week 2 versus a Falcons defense that allowed 137 rushing yards in their season opener.
outlooksByWeek.4: Saquon Barkley rushed for a season-high 147 yards last game for the Eagles while also scoring two touchdowns in the 15-12 triumph over the Saints.  With Philadelphia down two playmakers on the outside, Barkley dominated the touches, garnering over 20 opportunities for the third-straight contest.  Barkley now has five touchdowns over that span and is averaging an impressive 5.6 yards per tote.  If A.J. Brown and/or DeVonta Smith miss the Week 4 clash with the Bucs, Barkley could somehow find himself with even more touches.  Barkley has a stellar matchup with a Tampa Bay defense allowing 137.7 yards per tilt on the ground in 2024, which is 24th in the league.  The Bucs defense has also yielded six rushing scores already, the second-worst mark in the NFL to date.
outlooksByWeek.6: Saquon Barkley has gone over 100 scrimmage yards in every game thus far this season for the Eagles.  Barkley is averaging six yards per rush and over seven yards per reception in 2024.  Without the services of A.J. Brown and DeVonta Smith, the Philadelphia offense has had to lean even more heavily on Barkley.  Even if those playmakers return in Week 6 versus the Browns, Barkley should still garner double-digit touches easily.  Cleveland's run defense has also been rather suspect in 2024.  The Browns are allowing 141.6 rushing yards per tilt, which is 25th in the league.  In addition, Cleveland has yielded eight rushing scores, which is tied for 28th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.7: Saquon Barkley and the potential revenge game narrative cannot be ignored. In Week 7, Barkley's Eagles will face his old team, the New York Giants. Barkley left the Giants after six seasons and felt undervalued by the current regime in New York. On the field, Barkley will face a defense that has been surprisingly solid. The Giants are allowing 116.3 rushing yards per tilt, which is 15th in the league. However, New York has given up just three rushing scores in 2024, which is tied for fifth in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.8: Saquon Barkley torched his former team for 176 rushing yards this past Sunday. Barkley led the Eagles against his former club, the New York Giants, and managed 187 scrimmage yards and a touchdown in a dominating 28-3 win. Barkley has five rushing touchdowns through six games. He is averaging a robust 6.1 yards per carry, and is currently third in the NFL in rushing yards. He has a tasty matchup in Week 8 versus a subpar Bengals run defense.  The Bengals are allowing 136.1 rushing yards per clash, which is also 21st in the league. In addition, Cincy has surrendered eight rushing touchdowns, which is tied for 22nd in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.9: Saquon Barkley crossed the 100-yard rushing mark for the second-straight game for the Eagles. Barkley rushed 22 times for 108 yards in the 37-17 win over the Bengals. Barkley is second in the NFL in rushing yards behind Derrick Henry. In Week 9, Barkley will face a Jacksonville defense that has been surprisingly stingy against the run. The Jags are allowing just 111 yards rushing per tilt, which is ninth in the league. However, Jacksonville has given up nine rushing touchdowns, which is 20th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Saquon Barkley scored twice last game while racking up 199 scrimmage yards for the Eagles. Saquon has rushed for over 100 yards in three-straight contests. In Week 10, Barkley will face a reeling Dallas Cowboys squad that has lost three-straight contests. The Dallas defense has been torched on the ground in 2024, allowing 147.8 rushing yards per clash, which is 30th in the league. Dallas has also allowed 13 rushing touchdowns, which is 31st in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.11: Saquon Barkley was held under 100 yards rushing for the first time in four games for the Eagles. A minor left forearm injury as well as the lopsided nature of the blowout of the Cowboys both likely played a role in Barkley's fairly pedestrian output. Still, Barkley has received double-digit carries in every game this season, and should be primed for a bounce back performance in Week 11 versus a suspect Commanders run defense. Washington is allowing 142.7 rushing yards per game in 2024, which is 28th in the NFL. In addition, Washington has surrendered 10 rushing touchdowns in 2024, which is tied for 19th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.12: Saquon Barkley ran wild for the Eagles last game. Barkley rushed 26 times for 146 yards and two touchdowns in the win over the Commanders. He also caught two passes for 52 yards in the 26-18 triumph. Barkley has already crossed the 1,000-yard rushing mark just 10 games into the season. In Week 12, the Eagles will face a Rams defense that has been a bit better against the run than the pass. The Rams are allowing 223.3 passing yards per tilt, which is 22nd in the NFL. Los Angeles has yielded 18 passing scores in 2024, which is tied for 24th in the league. Meanwhile, the Rams have surrendered just seven rushing touchdowns this season, which is tied for seventh in the league. The Rams are allowing 127.3 yards per tilt on the ground, though, which is 18th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.13: Saquon Barkley torched the Los Angeles Rams for a career-high 255 rushing yards last game. Barkley also set the Eagles rushing record for a single contest. He scored two touchdowns as well, both of 70-plus yards. Barkley leads the NFL in rushing, has scored multiple touchdowns in five games in 2024, and has crossed the 100-yard rushing plateau five times in the last six contests. However, a difficult task lurks in Week 13 versus the Baltimore Ravens. Baltimore is allowing just 77.5 rushing yards per tilt, which is second in the NFL. In addition, the Ravens have given up just seven rushing touchdowns on the year, which is tied for sixth in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley left the rival Giants for the superior offense down the New Jersey Turnpike, one stacked with elite options at quarterback, wide receiver and, perhaps most importantly, along the still-dominant offensive line. Barkley's 2023 numbers may appear average, but blame the underwhelming New York offense, from the players to its direction. Still blessed with elite skills, a mostly healthy Barkley finished ninth among running backs at 15.9 fantasy points per game, and he may return to his 2022 numbers (1,312 rushing yards, 57 catches) in this top offense. Barkley is a first-round fantasy pick and potential top-three fantasy RB provided health (one never knows) and volume (no problems there).

outlooksByWeek.1: Bijan Robinson was surprisingly underutilized as a rookie last season, but beginning with Atlanta's matchup against a tough Steelers front in Week 1, he now projects for the workhorse role that his 215-plus pound, and 4.46-second 40 build and former No. 8 overall draft capital demands. Pittsburgh is a tough Week 1 opponent that last season was more vulnerable through the air than up front, but Robinson's three-down skillset makes him capable of overcoming even the most difficult matchups. In addition to working as Atlanta's top ball carrier, with Tyler Allgeier now relegated to a true backup role, Robinson could do most of his damage Week 1 as one of new quarterback Kirk Cousins' favorite pass-catchers in the intermediate area of the field.
outlooksByWeek.2: Bijan Robinson will look to do more with his deservedly elite workload Week 2 on the road against the Eagles. He wasn't tremendously efficient on 18 carries during Week 1's loss to the Steelers, turning that into just 68 yards on the ground, but it was encouraging to see Robinson account for the majority of Atlanta's 21 rushes. More encouraging was his chemistry with new QB Kirk Cousins, who completed all five of his targets to Robinson for 43 yards. Cousins figures to target Drake London (three targets) and Kyle Pitts (three targets) more heavily going forward, but that doesn't necessarily mean Robinson's usage will dip. The star running back may be Atlanta's top receiving threat in the intermediate area of the field.
outlooksByWeek.3: Bijan Robinson remains the lone true bright spot for Atlanta's offense heading into a Week 3 matchup against the reigning Super Bowl champions from Kansas City. The star running back exceeded 100 scrimmage yards versus Philadelphia in Week 2, while both Drake London and Kyle Pitts have been held below 100 yards combined in back-to-back weeks. Perhaps more impressive, Robinson averaged nearly seven yards per carry on the ground, despite the Eagles' solid defensive line being able to focus on shutting down the run. The Falcons could be more eager to pass than run versus Kansas City, though. Through two games Kansas City is allowing the second-most passing yards (513), but are 14th in rushing yards allowed (259).
outlooksByWeek.4: Bijan Robinson will look to bounce back Week 4 despite the Falcons facing a tough divisional matchup against the Saints defense. The second-year pro salvaged his day with a rushing touchdown during Atlanta's 22-17 loss to the Chiefs, a contest in which he was otherwise stymied. Robinson managed just 31 rushing yards on 16 carries, while also securing both of his targets for an additional 21 yards. That was only the second game of Robinson's young career being held below 2.0 yards per carry, and his usage remains far ahead of backup Tyler Allegier. Through three games this season, the Saints have allowed the eighth-fewest rushing yards (298) in the NFL, but Saquon Barkley just managed to gash New Orleans to the tone of 17-147-2 on the ground. Leaning on the ground game prove to be Atlanta's safest method of approach versus New Orleans.
outlooksByWeek.5: Bijan Robinson will look to bounce back as the Falcons ready themselves to take on the Buccaneers on Thursday Night Football in Week 5. The offense faces a short week of rest after a narrow divisional win over the Saints, a 26-24 affair in which Robinson actually saw one less carry than backup Tyler Allegier. Robinson notched a respectable 28 yards on seven attempts (4.0 YPC), but Allegier was undeniably the hot hand at running back, taking eight carries for 60 yards (7.5 YPC). Coming off a short week, Robinson and Allegier could again handle similar workloads to stay fresh, especially with Robinson nursing a hamstring issue to begin the week. Anything resembling a 50/50 split would be a stark difference after Robinson worked as the Falcons' clear top rusher during the first three weeks of the season.
outlooksByWeek.6: Bijan Robinson heads to Carolina in Week 6 looking for a bigger share of the workload against the league's most generous defense to running backs. Robinson had only 12 rushes in Week 5 as Kirk Cousins had 62 dropbacks in Atlanta's overtime win against the Buccaneers. Robinson likely will be more involved this week, if for no other reason than game script -- a fourth-quarter lead likely will give Robinson more carries as the Falcons look to burn clock. Robinson should also have more success against a weak Panthers run defense, which has allowed a league-leading nine rushing touchdowns to running backs this year.
outlooksByWeek.7: Bijan Robinson faces a leaky Seahawks defense in Week 7, hoping to build on the career day he had in Week 6. Robinson rushed 15 times for 95 yards and a career-high two touchdowns. He also caught three passes for 10 yards. It was the first time this season that Robinson topped 20 fantasy points in standard leagues. Tyler Allgeier also had a big game for the Falcons, rushing for 105 yards and a score. The two likely will again share the backfield this week, but both again could be productive. In the last three weeks, the Seahawks have allowed the fifth-most fantasy points per game in the league to running backs at 26.9.
outlooksByWeek.8: Bijan Robinson faces a middle-of-the-pack team in terms of running back fantasy points per game in Week 8, as the Falcons take on the Bucs. Luckily for him, he's coming off his first game of the season above 100 rushing yards, and he now has accrued 248 total yards and three touchdowns in the last two games. This means Robinson could still put up solid numbers against a relatively tough Tampa Bay defensive front, especially if he continues to out-pace running back Tyler Allgeier for carries as he did this past week versus the Seahawks (21-5).
outlooksByWeek.9: Bijan Robinson and Atlanta will face off against a recently struggling Cowboys squad in Week 9. Additionally, Dallas has let up the second-most standard fantasy points per game and third-most PPR points per game to running backs at this point in the year. Now coming off his third straight game with 100 or more scrimmage yards against the Bucs where he also recorded a season-high seven catches, the leading back is primed for another day with high output against the Boys.
outlooksByWeek.10: Bijan Robinson enters an incredibly favorable matchup as the Falcons take on the Saints in Week 10. Robinson now has 100 or more total scrimmage yards in the past four games for Atlanta, and he's found the end zone four times in that stretch. New Orleans' defense has let up the second-most fantasy points to running backs in the last four weeks and has let up 10 rushing touchdowns to RBs this season. This puts Robinson at a high probability of posting a  100-yard performance, especially as he's commanded such a high share of both carries and targets in the passing game at this point in the year.
outlooksByWeek.11: Bijan Robinson will look to build off his best rushing performance of the season as the Falcons play the Broncos in Week 11. Robinson rushed 20 times for 116 yards and two touchdowns in Atlanta's loss to the Saints this past Sunday, but this was against the third-worst defense in terms of points per game against running backs this year. The dynamic ball carrier will see a script flip as he matches up versus one of the better defenses against running backs in Denver, though his playmaking abilities have not been halted too badly against similar teams so far this season. The second-year now has amassed 100 or more scrimmage yards in the last five outings for the Falcons, and his current rate of usage primes him for another big week even versus a less favorable mountain matchup.
outlooksByWeek.13: Bijan Robinson should continue his hot output for the Falcons against the Chargers in Week 13. The second-year was held to just 63 total yards before the bye week versus the Broncos, but he did still have 12 carries and four targets in the passing game. Robinson broke a five-game streak of 105 total yards in the defeat before the bye, but he should be given plenty of opportunities to get back to that form even though Los Angeles does rank pretty well against running backs.

player.seasonOutlook: Robinson's rookie season was a mixed bag that included limited rushing contributions (15th or lower in carries, yards and TDs) but excellent receiving production (top five among RBs in routes, targets, yards and TDs), as well as terrific efficiency. Robinson's season felt underwhelming considering his early-first-round pedigree, but he finished fifth among RBs in snaps, sixth in yards and ninth in fantasy points. With Kirk Cousins now under center and Zac Robinson replacing run-heavy Arthur Smith as the team's play caller, a leap forward for Robinson seems likely in his second campaign. That will especially be the case if he manages more work near the goal line (only two carries inside the 5-yard line in 2023). Robinson should be one of the first RBs off the board on draft day.

outlooksByWeek.1: Puka Nacua has been a full participant in recent practices after suffering a knee injury in early August, and he is ready to start for the Rams in Week 1 at the Lions. While Detroit added much needed help to their secondary this offseason, they have a long way to go after allowing 28 receiving touchdowns in 2023, sixth worst in the NFL.  The return of a healthy Cooper Kupp might hurt Nacua's ceiling somewhat, but he still averaged over 8 targets per game when Kupp was active last season. Nacua remains a strong fantasy option to open the season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Puka Nacua is slated to be placed in IR after suffering a knee injury in the season opener. He managed 4 receptions for 35 yards before leaving the game midway through the second quarter. Tyler Johnson and Demarcus Robinson will likely move up the depth chart while Nacua is out, and tight end Colby Parkinson might also see increased usage in the passing game. The Rams play a Cardinals defense that has one of the league's worst pass rushes in Week 2, and they are coming off of a Week 1 performance where they allowed 232 receiving yards to Buffalo.
outlooksByWeek.8: Puka Nacua is questionable for the Rams' Week 8 game against the Vikings. Reports indicate that the Rams are hopeful that he will be available to play, and he practiced in a limited capacity early in the week. It will be difficult to project Nacua's playing time in his first game back after his PCL sprain he suffered in Week 1. It would make sense for the Rams to ease Nacua back into the team with a part-time role, which would make him difficult to trust in fantasy in Week 8. Minnesota has allowed 260 passing yards per game in 2024, third most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.9: Puka Nacua got off to a strong start in his first appearance back from injury in Week 8. Nacua reeled in seven of nine targets for 106 yards, and he had two carries for five yards. Nacua played in just over half of the Rams' offensive snaps, but Matthew Stafford made a point of getting him the ball whenever he was on the field. Nacua's role in this offense should continue to grow moving forward as he moves on from his knee injury he suffered at the start of the season. In Week 9, the Rams have a divisional game against the Seahawks. Seattle's defense has been near the league average this season allowing 208 passing yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.10: Puka Nacua was ejected in the second quarter in Week 9 after throwing a punch at an opponent. Up to that point, Nacua had played in most of the Rams' offensive snaps, catching one of four targets for 11 yards. Nacua entered the game with a knee injury, so despite the lack of production, it was promising to see him healthy enough to play a significant role in the offense. Matthew Stafford will likely continue to target Nacua heavily in Week 10, making him a solid option despite a tricky matchup against Miami's secondary. The Dolphins are allowing 183 passing yards per game, fourth best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.11: Puka Nacua earned 14 targets in Week 10, finishing with nine catches for 98 yards. Nacua ended up leading the Rams in targets, receiving yards, and receptions. Nacua has been a target magnet since returning from injury, earning nine targets per game in the last three weeks. With that kind of utilization, Nacua will be a strong fantasy option moving forward when the Rams take on the Patriots in Week 11. New England has allowed 209 passing yards per game this season, ranking 16th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.12: Puka Nacua had another strong performance in Week 11, catching seven of nine targets for 123 yards and his first touchdown of the season. In his four appearances since coming back from injury, Nacua has earned nine targets per game, and Matthew Stafford should continue to frequently target Nacua in Week 12 when the Rams face off against the Eagles. It will be a tough matchup for Nacua, as the Eagles have one of the league's best passing defenses. Philadelphia has allowed only 19.5 receptions per game this season, ninth best in the league, and the unit allows just 173 passing yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.13: Puka Nacua led the Rams in Week 12 with 13 targets, finishing with nine catches for 117 yards. Nacua is earning just under 10 targets per game in his past five starts, and he has logged more than 100 receiving yards in that same timespan. Nacua should continue to be peppered with targets moving forward, and he is a great fantasy option in a Week 13 matchup against New Orleans. The Saints have allowed 257 passing yards per game this season, third most in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Rostered in just 1.6% of ESPN Fantasy leagues ahead of Week 1 last season, Nacua proved to be the waiver wire's most generous offering. The first-year slotman immediately filled injured Cooper Kupp's shoes to lead the team in routes, targets, catches and yards, while regularly dazzling after the catch (639 YAC, WR5). Nacua's volume dipped after Kupp returned, but the BYU product continued to churn, setting both the NFL rookie receiving yards and receptions records. Given Kupp's age and injury history, Nacua is a good bet to remain Matthew Stafford's most productive pass-catcher again in 2024. He's a solid fantasy WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chase Brown shifted up the running back depth chart in Cincinnati due to the departure of Joe Mixon, though he'll still split work with new addition Zack Moss. The Bengals have been careful to not specify exactly how touches will be allocated, though Brown proved to be a capable big-play threat in his rookie season by breaking off two runs of at least 20 yards on only 44 attempts. He draws a Week 1 matchup against the Patriots, who were a stout run defense in 2023, allowing only 93.2 rushing yards per game. New England still has a solid linebacking corps but will be without Christian Barmore due to injury and also traded away Matthew Judon, thinning their defensive line.
outlooksByWeek.2: Chase Brown got a lot of hype during Bengals training camp, but he was limited to only six total touches in Week 1 while playing behind Zack Moss. His 33% snap rate suggests he'll need to rely on big plays to become fantasy relevant, something that isn't likely to be easy in a Week 2 matchup against the Chiefs. The Kansas City defense limited Ravens RB Derrick Henry to only 3.5 yards per rush in Week 1, though they were relatively vulnerable through the air to Justice Hill. The latter could be Brown's best path to fantasy value, but he is not a comfortable start for the time being.
outlooksByWeek.3: Chase Brown gained considerable hype throughout Cincinnati's training camp, but he has clearly worked as the backup running back through two weeks. He did showcase some big-play potential on his four rushes in Week 2, averaging an impressive 7.8 yards per carry. If he continues to make the most of his opportunity, his role could expand as the season progresses- particularly because Zack Moss has been unremarkable early on. However, heading into a Week 3 matchup against the Commanders, Brown is a risky play due to his limited projected volume.
outlooksByWeek.4: Chase Brown has worked behind Zack Moss in the Cincinnati backfield through three games this season, but he has started to make the case for a bigger role by averaging 7.8 and 8.9 yards per carry on limited touches in the last two weeks. He should have the opportunity to continue working efficiently in Week 4 against the Panthers, as Carolina has allowed 4.6 yards per carry -- the 10th-highest mark in the league. Ultimately, Brown is an unreliable option due to his volume, but he is among the most intriguing stash options in standard-sized leagues.
outlooksByWeek.5: Chase Brown's role increased in the Cincinnati offense in Week 4, as he tallied a season-high 17 touches while playing 42% of offensive snaps. He has shown strong efficiency with his opportunity through four weeks by averaging 6.3 yards per carry, which bodes well for the potential for his role to continue to grow. In the short term, Brown will face a stingy Ravens' run defense in Week 5, jeopardizing his efficiency and viability in fantasy lineups.
outlooksByWeek.6: In Week 5, Chase Brown earned double-digit carries for the second consecutive game and has moved into an even split for work with Zack Moss. However, he could get a chance to serve as a true lead back in a Week 6 matchup against the Giants, pending the health of Moss after he suffered an ankle injury late in Cincinnati's Week 5 loss to the Ravens. If Moss is able to suit up, Brown is a risky start even with his increased involvement and big-play ability, as he hasn't gotten much work at the goal line or as a pass catcher through five games.
outlooksByWeek.7: Chase Brown took over the Bengals' backfield for the second half of their Week 6 win over the Giants after Zack Moss lost a fumble. Brown still has flaws in his game -- he had a fumble of his own late in the contest that went out of bounds -- but he seems to have finally gained the trust of the coaching staff and has shown explosiveness with a pair of 20-plus yard gains on the ground across the last three weeks. Brown isn't likely to have the backfield to himself in Week 7 against the Browns, but he should have the chance to serve as the lead back against a mediocre run defense. He's a reasonable RB2.
outlooksByWeek.8: Chase Brown has taken over as Cincinnati's lead back and matched his season-high of 17 touches in Week 7 against Cleveland. He wasn't able to make much of that opportunity by averaging only 2.9 yards per carry, and he'll face another stiff defensive matchup in Week 8 against an Eagles defense that has allowed the sixth-fewest fantasy points to opposing running backs on the season. Brown also continues to be used minimally as a pass catcher, hurting his range of outcomes. Consider him as a low-end RB2 or FLEX option.
outlooksByWeek.9: Chase Brown served as the clear lead back for the Bengals for the second consecutive game in Week 8, though he's been ineffective in each performance. In total, he's managed only 76 yards on 27 carries in those two contests. Brown also remains uninvolved as a pass catcher, making him reliant upon touchdowns or improved efficiency to be a useful fantasy option. He'll head into a Week 9 matchup against the Raiders, a unit that has allowed seven rushing scores and 4.67 yards per carry to opposing running backs this season. Consider Brown a solid FLEX option.
outlooksByWeek.10: Chase Brown finally got the chance to lead the Bengals' backfield without competition in Week 9, and he delivered 157 total yards from scrimmage with a receiving score. Zack Moss is expected to miss the rest of the regular season with a neck injury, which could clear the way for Brown to set a lot of work in the short term. Cincinnati's acquisition of Khalil Herbert on Tuesday muddies things a bit down the road, but Brown should see the majority of work in Week 10 against Baltimore on a short week. He's a decent FLEX or low-end RB2 due to projected volume, but the Ravens have allowed the seventh-fewest points per game to opposing running backs this season.
outlooksByWeek.11: Chase Brown has pounced on the opportunity to lead the Cincinnati backfield since Zack Moss (neck) has gone down, as he's topped 20 touches in each of Weeks 9 and 10. Most notable has been his 14 receptions on 16 targets in that span, helping him cover up some inefficiency as a rusher. Brown isn't likely to find much running room in a Week 11 matchup against the Chargers, who have allowed the third-fewest fantasy points per game to opposing running backs. He's still an RB2 based on expected volume, but don't expect his second 100-yard rushing performance of the season.
outlooksByWeek.13: Chase Brown has topped 20 total touches in three consecutive games in the absence of Zack Moss (neck) and remains locked in as the starter in Cincinnati. His results have been mediocre as a runner, as he's averaged just 4.0 yards per carry in that span. However, his volume as a receiver has been a solid supplement to his production, as he's recorded at least five receptions in each of his last three matchups. A Week 13 divisional showdown against the Steelers presents a mediocre matchup, making Brown a solid RB2 based on his overall volume and ability as a pass catcher.

player.seasonOutlook: Heading into his second pro season, Brown will occupy the No. 2 role behind Zack Moss in the Bengals' backfield. Brown has the ability to find interior daylight as a runner, plus he flashed as a receving target as a rookie. Last season, Brown averaged 14.4 yards per reception on screens, using his vision and contact balance to win in space. He is a smart insurance play behind Moss, and his receiving usage creates flex value in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Josh Jacobs joins the Packers after a disappointing season with the Raiders, where he rushed for a career-low 805 yards and six touchdowns. His dip in production was due to a combination of lackluster quarterback play, questionable coaching decisions, and missing the final four games of the season due to injury. However, the 26-year-old is only two years removed from leading the NFL with 1,653 rushing yards in 2022 and is expected to serve as a workhorse back in a more formidable Green Bay offense. In Week 1, Jacobs faces a Philadelphia defense that ranked 10th against the run in 2023, allowing 103.4 rushing yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.2: Josh Jacobs delivered a solid performance in his debut, accumulating 104 total yards with 84 rushing yards on 16 carries and 20 receiving yards on two catches in a 34-29 loss to the Eagles. Despite a sluggish start, Jacobs demonstrated his explosiveness in the second half, highlighted by a 32-yard run that contributed to a Green Bay field goal. With Jordan Love sidelined and Malik Willis still familiarizing himself with the offense, Jacobs could see a more prominent role in Week 2. The Colts struggled against the run last season, ranking 24th in rushing yards allowed per game with an average of 123.2 yards. Last week, they allowed Joe Mixon 159 rushing yards and a touchdown on 30 carries, underscoring their continued vulnerability against the run.
outlooksByWeek.3: Josh Jacobs is expected to garner another big workload for the Packers in Week 3 against the Titans. With starting quarterback Jordan Love on the shelf with an MCL sprain, Green Bay relied heavily on the ground game, running the ball a staggering 53 times while throwing just 14 times in an unexpected victory over the Colts. Jacobs accounted for 32 of those carries, amassing 151 yards. The Packers are likely to stick with a similar run-heavy approach against a Tennessee defense that has allowed the eighth-fewest rushing yards to opposing running backs this season. However, the Titans did give up 75 receiving yards and two touchdowns on nine catches to Jets backs Breece Hall and Braelon Allen last week.
outlooksByWeek.4: Josh Jacobs is averaging 92.7 rushing yards per game but has yet to score this season. He thrived in Week 2 behind Green Bay's run-heavy approach with Malik Willis under center, though last week was tougher, as he managed just 43 yards on 14 carries. Despite the down performance, Jacobs remains the Packers' lead back heading into Week 4. He'll face a stout Vikings defense that has given up just 171 rushing yards to running backs this season, ranking third in the NFL. Notably, 100 of those yards came from Jordan Mason in Week 2.
outlooksByWeek.5: Josh Jacobs will look to get more involved as Green Bay prepares for a key road matchup against the Rams in Week 5. He was efficient in the Packers' 31-29 loss to the Vikings, in which he rushed nine times for 51 yards and brought in four of six targets for 27 yards, but it was notable to see Emaunuel Wilson handle a roughly equal share of touches. Wilson, for his part, was less efficient, taking eight carries for 27 yards while failing to reel in his only target. In all likelihood, had Green Bay not fallen prey to a gamescript that involved being down 28-7 entering the second half and having to largely abandon the run, Jacobs would've held onto his usual bellcow role. He'll try to do so Week 5 against an injured Los Angeles front, a game in which the Packers could take a turn getting out to an early lead.
outlooksByWeek.6: Josh Jacobs will remain a featured piece of Green Bay's offense as the team prepares to host the Cardinals in Week 6. The veteran running back logged his second game of the season with 20-plus touches during Week 5's win over the Rams, in which he rushed 19 times for 73 yards and a touchdown and secured his lone target for 21 yards. Despite having already logged 90 carries through five appearances, Jacobs' rushing touchdown versus Los Angeles was also his first time reaching the end zone this season. Jacobs has been efficient on the year (4.5 YPC) and he's already logged as many runs of 20-plus yards (three) as he did in 13 games with the Raiders last season. He'll continue leading Green Bay's backfield, with Emanuel Wilson working in the No. 2 role, at home versus Arizona.
outlooksByWeek.7: Josh Jacobs will continue to lead Green Bay's backfield with a difficult home matchup against the Texans on deck for Week 7. The veteran running back rushed 18 times for 62 yards and caught all three of his targets for 28 yards during the Packers' 34-13 win over Arizona, but he was again held out of the end zone. Across six appearances this season, Jacobs' only touchdown came on the ground versus the Rams, a somewhat exceptional statistic considering that he's handled 108 carries and been targeted 14 times already. Jacobs now faces a tough matchup against Houston's defensive front, which allowed just 2.1 yards per carry to the Patriots in Week 5, albeit against a New England roster that was without top RB Rhamondre Stevenson. Jacobs' workload is guaranteed and the Packers are able to consistently find their way into scoring position, though, so positive TD regression should come the former Raiders' way before long.
outlooksByWeek.8: Josh Jacobs will look to keep up his momentum as the Packers work to earn a fourth consecutive victory heading into a Week 8 matchup at Jacksonville. During Green Bay's 24-22 win over Houston in Week 7, Jacobs rushed 12 times for 76 yards (6.3 YPC) while securing five of a season-high eight targets for 16 yards and one score. Jacobs' receiving score was the first of his career, despite it coming in his 80th NFL appearance and 212th career reception. He once again doubled up backup Emanuel Wilson in terms of touch totals, working as the clear No. 1 option out of the backfield for the Packers. More consistent opportunities to reach the end zone is the only potential area of improvement Jacobs could truly ask for in terms of production, so it was encouraging to see him draw his second target in the red zone of the 2024 campaign. Against the Jaguars' unimpressive defense, which ranks seventh against the run mostly as a result of ranking dead last against the pass, Jacobs stands to see more opportunities to correct his TD totals.
outlooksByWeek.9: Josh Jacobs will be central to Green Bay's game plan on offense as the team prepares for a pivotal matchup against the Lions in Week 9. With Jordan Love nursing a groin strain that forced him out early Week 8, Jacobs was given an opportunity to carry the Packers' offense. He did so to the tune of 25 carries for 127 yards and two touchdowns, while also losing two yards on his lone catch. That was Jacobs' second-highest carry and yardage total of the season, and even if Love manages to suit up versus Detroit, the first-year Packer figures to again serve as this offense's lynchpin in order to take some pressure off his quarterback. The 26-year-old has been both efficient and crucial for Green Bay this season regardless of whether Love or Malik Willis has had to start under center, but now faces the sizable task of overcoming a Lions defense that has allowed the fifth-fewest rushing yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.11: Josh Jacobs will continue to lead Green Bay's backfield as the team prepares for a Week 11 divisional matchup in Chicago. Coming off a bye, Jacobs has had the opportunity to benefit from some much-needed rest, as he averaged a tremendous 19.2 touches per game during the first nine weeks of the season. A week of recuperation will help to alleviate the tread on Jacobs' tires, which started to show prior to the Packers' bye - during the second half of Green Bay's loss to Detroit in Week 9, Jacobs logged just three carries, while backups Chris Brooks and Emanuel Wilson saw more involvement. The impending return of rookie MarShawn Lloyd from IR will give the Packers further options to shoulder the backfield burden, but Jacobs remains the clear No. 1 rusher for this offense.
outlooksByWeek.12: Josh Jacobs will continue to operate as a focal point of Green Bay's offensive engine as the team prepares for a Week 12 home matchup against the 49ers. The No.1 running back rushed 18 times for 76 yards and one score during the team's narrow 20-19 win over Chicago, yet another efficient performance to mark his inaugural season with the Packers. Jacobs also served as Green Bay's second leading receiver versus Chicago, with four catches for 58 yards. Jacobs has now exceeded 100 scrimmage yards in five of 10 appearances throughout the 2024 regular season, but he faces a tough matchup against San Francisco, who rank eighth against the rush.
outlooksByWeek.13: Josh Jacobs will look to keep up his tremendous momentum as the Packers prepare for a Week 13 home game on Thanksgiving against Miami. After briefly exiting Green Bay's 38-10 trouncing of the 49ers, Jacobs quickly retook the field to finish the day with an impressive 26 carries for 106 yards, not to mention three rushing TDs. Despite Jacobs having totaled just four rushing touchdowns in his 10 prior appearances with the Packers, his three-score effort against San Francisco was enough to surpass his totals from 2023. Jacobs has been highly efficient as the lead man of Green Bay's backfield, averaging 4.7 yards per carry on the season. He'll be well-positioned to continue finding success on Thanksgiving against a Dolphins defense that ranks just middle-of-the-pack against the run, but No. 8 against the pass.

player.seasonOutlook: Jacobs joins the Packers after spending his first five years with the Raiders. In 2023, Jacobs resumed his go-to-back role and finished second in touches per game. However, despite that volume, Jacobs was RB17 in fantasy points per game, due to career lows in rushing yards, touchdowns and yards per rush. At 26 years old, Jacobs reprises his lead-back duties in Green Bay, replacing Aaron Jones and sharing the backfield with rookie MarShawn Lloyd. Jacobs is one of only five RBs with at least 50 targets in each of the past three seasons, and he gets enough passing-game work to maintain a high weekly floor. With another heavy workload on the horizon, Jacobs is a top-15 running back.

outlooksByWeek.1: Trey McBride will open the season as Arizona's starting tight end in a Week 1 visit to Buffalo, where he figures to feature prominently after logging just over 7 receptions per game in the second half of the 2023 season. The Bills have a good passing defense, and they allowed just under 45 receiving yards to tight ends per game last season, 8th best in the NFL. McBride led the Cardinals with 106 targets last season, which was 7th best among tight ends. While McBride now has to compete with rookie Marvin Harrison for opportunities, he still should be frequently targeted as Kyler Murray's secondary target in the Cardinals' offense.
outlooksByWeek.2: Trey McBride and the Cardinals will look to bounce back after losing their season opener with a Week 2 divisional match against the Rams. McBride caught five passes for just 30 yards, though he did lead Arizona with nine receiving targets. Few tight ends earn as many opportunities as McBride, who should have a strong fantasy role even as the Cardinals try to get Marvin Harrison more involved in the offense moving forward. In Week 1, the Rams allowed opposing tight ends five catches for 47 receiving yards.
outlooksByWeek.3: Trey McBride caught all six of his targets for 67 yards over the weekend. Arizona cruised to an early lead against the Rams over the weekend, which pushed the Cardinals into a run heavy game script. His six targets on 21 passing attempts show that even with Marvin Harrison succeeding in this offense, McBride can still get plenty of receiving work. In Week 3, Arizona hosts the Lions, who have allowed 251 receiving yards per game in 2024. Detroit has allowed just four receptions for 47 yards so far this season to the tight end position.
outlooksByWeek.4: Trey McBride was targeted six times, and he caught three passes for 25 receiving yards. It was McBride's least productive outing of the season, and he was placed in the concussion protocol after taking a hit in the fourth quarter. McBride now has to clear the concussion protocol, putting his Week 4 status against the Commanders in doubt. If McBride is unable to play, Elijah Higgins and Tip Reiman would get more playing time, and Higgins is the option who has contributed more to the passing game this season. In Week 4, Arizona goes up against a struggling Commanders defense. Washington is allowing more than 250 passing yards per game in 2024, making them one of the worst passing defenses in the league.
outlooksByWeek.6: Trey McBride earned nine receptions over the weekend, and he recorded six catches for 63 yards. McBride missed Week 4 with a concussion and was an addition to the injury report with a ribs injury last week, so it was promising to see McBride play well and return to a full time role. His eight targets led Arizona, and he should continue to be heavily targeted by Kyler Murray as the season continues. In Week 6, the Cardinals play the Packers, who have allowed 232 passing yards per game this season. The Packers have allowed the 11th most receiving yards to tight ends this season, and they allow 49 yards per game to the position.
outlooksByWeek.7: Trey McBride hauled in all of his team-high eight targets for 96 yards over the weekend. McBride was Murray's top target in the passing game after Marvin Harrison exited the game early with a concussion. McBride's 7.6 targets per game this season is second best in the league at the tight end position, and he might see even more work if Harrison is unable to clear the concussion protocol. In Week 7, the Cardinals go up against a Chargers defense that has allowed 192 passing yards per game in 2024, eighth best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.8: Trey McBride caught five of his seven targets for 51 yards in Week 7 against the Chargers. McBride has been a very consistent option this season, and his 7.5 targets per game in 2024 is second best among tight ends. Expect McBride to continue to be targeted frequently by Kyler Murray moving forward in Week 8 when the Cardinals face off against the Dolphins. Miami has allowed just 155 passing yards per game in 2024, best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.9: Trey McBride had his first 100+ receiving yard performance of the season, catching nine of 11 targets for 124 yards. As has been the story for much of the season, McBride led Arizona's receivers in targets. Even in a Week 9 matchup against a Bears defense that has been difficult to score on this season, McBride should be a strong fantasy option given his consistently high target share in this offense. Chicago's defense has allowed 199 passing yards per game in 2024, 11th best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Trey McBride caught three of four targets for 35 yards in Week 9. He also scored a two-yard rushing touchdown off of a redzone carry, which salvaged his day for fantasy. While it's concerning to see McBride targeted just four times, he still had a good target share as Arizona only attempted 20 passes due to positive game script. McBride should continue to be targeted frequently, but his ceiling is hurt by the fact that Arizona is bottom ten in the league in passing attempts per game this season. In Week 10, Arizona goes up against a solid Jets defense. The Jets' passing defense has allowed 158 passing yards per game this season, second best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.12: Trey McBride has been Kyler Murray's preferred target this season. So far, McBride leads the Cardinals with 7.2 targets for 61.3 receiving yards per game. McBride's weekly ceiling for fantasy is hurt by the fact that Arizona has attempted the second fewest passes per game this season, but he is still a top five tight end this season in receptions, targets, and receiving yards per game. In Week 12, Arizona goes up against the Seahawks. Seattle has had an average passing defense this season, allowing 211 yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.13: Trey McBride dominated as a pass catcher for Arizona in Week 12. McBride caught 12 of 15 targets for 133 receiving yards. All of those statistics were season-highs for McBride, who appears to be Kyler Murray's preferred receiving target ahead of Marvin Harrison in this offense. While it is unlikely that Murray matches his season high 37 passing attempts in Week 13 when the Cardinals face off against the Vikings, McBride should still figure to play an important role in the passing game. Minnesota has allowed 243 passing yards per game this season, fifth most in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: McBride put together a breakout sophomore effort, leading all Arizona pass-catchers in targets (108), receptions (81) and yards (825). The Colorado State product averaged more than eight targets per contest from Weeks 8 through 18, after Zach Ertz was placed on injured reserve and eventually waived. McBride quickly earned Kyler Murray's trust, drawing a team-high five end zone looks and recording a catch rate of 80% over the final eight games of the season. He figures to remain an integral part of the Cardinals' aerial attack heading into 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ladd McConkey was never the top option at Georgia during his college career, but he was extremely efficient on the volume he did get, and a strong showing at the Combine convinced the Chargers to select him in the second round of the 2024 Draft. McConkey combines decent size with good speed and elite route-running skills, a combination that could make him the most natural replacement for Keenan Allen as Justin Herbert's top target. Holdover Joshua Palmer and 2023 first-round Quentin Johnston are also competing for positioning on the depth chart, but McConkey appears to have the most upside of the trio. He'll make his NFL debut in Week 1 against a Raiders secondary that finished in the bottom half of the league in 2023 in receiving touchdowns allowed and yards per target allowed to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.2: Ladd McConkey posted modest numbers in his NFL debut in Week 1 but led the Chargers in receptions, receiving yards and targets, and he caught QB Justin Herbert's only touchdown pass. The 2024 second-round pick could take over the No. 1 wideout position quickly, with only Joshua Palmer standing in his way, but the Chargers emphasis on running the ball will limit the ceiling of its passing game. McConkey's speed and sharp route-running give him strong yards-after-catch upside though and should allow him to exploit defenses worn out trying to slow down the Chargers' backfield. He'll need to be efficient with his targets again in Week 2 against a Panthers team that got routed in its opener, and which could fall behind quickly again.
outlooksByWeek.3: Ladd McConkey has shown flashes of his upside to begin his NFL career, catching seven of 11 targets for 65 yards and a touchdown through two games. The 2024 second-round pick could emerge as Justin Herbert's most trusted downfield option in time, but last week it was second-year wideout Quentin Johnston who commanded Herbert's attention. The Chargers' passing game as a whole doesn't figure to produce big volume under OC Greg Roman, so there may not be many opportunities for both wideouts to be productive in the same week. McConkey will face a tough Steelers secondary in Week 3 that's given up only 17 receptions to WRs through two weeks, tied for fourth in the league.
outlooksByWeek.4: Ladd McConkey continues to adjust to the NFL, catching three of six targets for 44 yards in a Week 3 loss to the Steelers. The 2024 second-round pick has had an erratic role in the Chargers' offense so far, falling to a 49.3% snap share in Week 2 before jumping back to a 71.7% share in Week 3, but encouragingly, McConkey has been able to maintain steady target volume. He could be working without Justin Herbert in Week 4 due to the quarterback's high-ankle sprain, but even if he's catching passes from backup Taylor Heinicke, McConkey might be able to produce against a Kansas City secondary that's given up three TDs to wideouts through three games.
outlooksByWeek.6: Ladd McConkey has had a solid start to his NFL career, leading the Chargers with 15 catches and 176 yards on 24 targets through four games. The volume is modest, but the team's run-heavy offense limits the upside of all its WRs. McConkey also has two touchdowns, and he and second-year wideout Quentin Johnston have accounted for all five of Justin Herbert's passing TDs so far. McConkey could have a tough time putting up big numbers in Week 6 against a Broncos secondary that's allowed the second-fewest receiving yards per game in the league to wide receivers.
outlooksByWeek.7: Ladd McConkey landed a career-high eight targets in Week 6, and over the last three games for the Chargers he's posted a tidy 12-154-1 line on 21 targets. The rookie is emerging as Justin Herbert's top wideout, and as the quarterback gets healthier, McConkey's role could lead to more production. However, he's topped 44 receiving yards only once so far, so his upside remains more theoretical than actual. McConkey could break out in Week 7 against a Cardinals secondary that ranks in the bottom 10 in receiving yards and touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.8: Ladd McConkey has yet to break out, but the Chargers rookie has been surprisingly consistent. He's caught multiple passes in six straight games to begin his NFL career and has recorded at least six targets in five of the six, as he establishes chemistry with quarterback Justin Herbert. Herbert is getting heathier, which should result in a boost for the team's entire passing game, but McConkey also appears poised to develop into the QB's top downfield option, a job that has remained vacant since the offseason departures of Keenan Allen and Mike Williams. McConkey could pop in Week 8 against a Saints secondary that ranks in the bottom six in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.9: Ladd McConkey broke out with a huge performance in Week 8 against the Saints. The rookie wideout caught all six of his targets for 111 yards and two touchdowns, and he could be emerging as Justin Herbert's top downfield option. The Chargers have been waiting for someone to step up following the offseason departures of Keenan Allen and Mike Williams, and McConkey is the first player to rise to the challenge. He could stay hot in Week 9 against a Browns secondary that ranks in the bottom 10 in receiving yards and TDs allowed to wideouts.
outlooksByWeek.10: Ladd McConkey' volume continues to be steady in the Chargers' passing game. The rookie wideout has notched between six and eight targets in six straight games, posting a 28-375-3 line on 41 targets over that stretch. Quentin Johnston had the bigger performance in Week 9, but with Justin Herbert getting healthier, there could be enough volume to go around for both young WRs. McConkey will take on a Titans secondary in Week 10 that ranks in the top seven in catches, receiving yards and touchdowns allowed to wide receivers.
outlooksByWeek.11: Ladd McConkey registered just two targets in the Chargers Week 10 win over the Titans, his lowest volume of the season, but he caught both for 52 yards. The 2024 second-round pick has been the Chargers' most consistent wideout, topping 40 receiving yards in seven straight games, but the team's run-heavy offense has prevented him from collecting more than eight targets in any game. With QB Justin Herbert now fully healthy, McConkey's volume could increase. He could produce big numbers in Week 11 against a Bengals secondary that ranks in the bottom 10 in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.12: Ladd McConkey set career highs with 123 receiving yards on nine targets in a Week 11 win over the Bengals. The rookie has emerged as the Chargers' top wideout, and over the last four games he's posted a 19-350-2 line on 24 targets. With Justin Herbert fully healthy, McConkey seems poised for a big finish to his first NFL season. He'll face a vulnerable Ravens secondary in Week 12 that ranks in the bottom two in the league in catches, receiving yards and touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.13: Ladd McConkey has solidified his spot as the Chargers' top wide receiver. The 2024 second-round pick has topped 50 yards in five straight games, amassing a 25-433-2 line on 30 targets over that stretch. McConkey has forged a strong connection with Justin Herbert in a short period of time and has effectively replaced Keenan Allen in the Chargers offense as a reliable possession option with some big-play ability. McConkey will look to keep rolling in Week 13 against a Falcons secondary that is tied for 27th in receptions allowed to WRs this season.

player.seasonOutlook: Though Puka Nacua did it just last season, it's not common historically that a second-day draft pick emerges as his team's go-to receiver. McConkey has a very real chance to do just that, considering the team's aggressive move to trade up for him at No. 34 overall, addressing what was an especially weak spot on the team. He's a polished route-runner who, despite a disappointing and injury-limited senior season at Georgia, excelled at the combine (4.39 40 time), a reminder of his elite speed and quickness. Expect McConkey to get an extended look during the preseason, with a high probability of emerging as Justin Herbert's preferred target before the 2024 season concludes. There's WR3 upside here.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyrone Tracy enters his rookie campaign with the New York Giants with a chance to make an instant impact.  Saquon Barkley has taken his talents to Philadelphia, leaving a massive playmaking void for the G-Men out of the backfield.  Devin Singletary is the starter, but averaged a career-low 4.2 yards per tote last season, and may not shoulder the every-down rushing load due to his lack of size.  Tracy, a converted wideout, is a physical runner who impressed in preseason.  In Week 1, Tracy will face a Vikings defense that was fairly stingy against the run in 2023, allowing just 98.7 yards per tilt on the ground, which was eighth in the league.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tyrone Tracy saw little action in his NFL debut for the Giants.  Tracy managed three touches for a total of seven scrimmage yards in the 28-6 loss to the Vikings.  Tracy and Eric Gray appear to be battling for touches behind starter Devin Singletary.  As the Giants fell behind early in this contest, they were forced to largely abandon the run, allowing for even fewer running back touches than likely expected.  In Week 2, the Giants will have a chance for better results versus a mediocre Washington run defense. The Commanders allowed 112 rushing yards in their season opener, which was 15th in the NFL, though Tracy remains firmly behind the aforementioned Singletary on the depth chart.
outlooksByWeek.3: Tyrone Tracy managed just one carry for the Giants last game.  Devin Singletary remains the undisputed No. 1 running back, and took 16 carries for 95 yards and a touchdown in the 21-18 loss to the Commanders.  Coach Brian Daboll looks poised to give the shifty, diminutive Singletary virtually every chance to touch the ball out of the backfield, leaving the rookie Tracy to merely pick up the scraps.  In Week 3, the Giants will face a Browns defense allowing 114.5 yards per tilt on the ground, which is 14th in the NFL, though Tracy is unlikely to see many touches.
outlooksByWeek.4: Tyrone Tracy is coming off the best game of his young career for the Giants, taking seven touches for 40 scrimmage yards in the win over the Browns.  Tracy remains firmly behind starter Devin Singletary on the depth chart, but appears to be slowly gaining the trust of the coaching staff.   Singletary continues to garner the majority of the running back touches for the Giants, having received double-digit carries in each of the first three outings.  Even with touches likely to be limited, Tracy has an extremely favorable matchup in Week 4 versus a Cowboys defense that has been gutted on the ground thus far in 2024.  Dallas is allowing 185.7 rushing yards per clash, while also yielding eight rushing touchdowns in just three games.  Both of those statistics are dead last in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.5: Tyrone Tracy is expected to start Week 5 at the Seahawks as Devin Singletary is doubtful to play with a groin injury. Tracy has emerged as the clear-cut No. 2 running back for the Giants behind Singletary, though, so far at least, has offered little in terms of upside and production thanks to a mediocre offense. Tracy managed 21 scrimmage yards on five touches in Week 4.  This week, though, the Giants face a Seahawks defense that has been better against the pass than the run. Seattle allows 116.3 yards per game on the ground, which is 15th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.6: Tyrone Tracy rushed for 129 yards on 18 carries in place of the injured Devin Singletary, helping vault the New York Giants to a stunning win over the Seattle Seahawks. After fellow running back Eric Gray suffered a disastrous fumble on the goal line early in the game, the rookie Tracy took over and broke off several big runs for the G-Men en route to the career day. It remains to be seen if Singletary will be able to suit up for the Week 6 clash with the Bengals, but if he cannot, Tracy would likely be called upon again to shoulder the majority of the rushing load. Cincinnati has been abysmal against the run in 2024, allowing 151.4 yards per game on the ground, which is 30th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.7: Tyrone Tracy has excelled in the absence of starting running back Devin Singletary for the New York Giants.  For the second-straight game, Tracy managed over 100 scrimmage yards.  He also found the end zone for his first NFL touchdown. While Singletary could return in Week 7 versus the Eagles, at a minimum, Tracy has earned himself more touches in the offense.  The Eagles run defense has been mediocre against the run in 2024. Philadelphia is allowing 123 rushing yards per tilt, which is 17th in the NFL. However, the Eagles have yielded just three rushing touchdowns thus far in 2024, which is tied for fifth in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.8: Tyrone Tracy saw his run as the Giants starter end last game, as Devin Singletary returned to action for the New York Giants following a two-game absence.  Neither back had much success in an ugly 28-3 loss to the Eagles, though.  Singletary rushed five times for 18 yards, while also catching his lone target for three yards out of the backfield. Meanwhile, Tracy rushed six times for 23 years, and caught three passes for nine yards.  This backfield situation has all the makings of a timeshare moving forward. The matchup in Week 8 versus the Pittsburgh Steelers is not ideal either.  Pittsburgh has one of the top run defenses in the NFL, surrendering just 81 yards per clash on the ground, which is third in the league. In addition, the Steelers have allowed just three rushing touchdowns in seven games, which is tied for second in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.9: Tyrone Tracy snatched the Giants' starting running back job from Devin Singletary, only to leave a Week 8 loss twice due to injury. The first issue involved his shoulder, though Tracy was able to return to the game. The second involved a potential concussion, which sidelined him for the remainder of the contest. Tracy had rushed 20 times for 145 yards and a touchdown despite the injury-plagued outing. Unfortunately, his status is in question for a Week 9 clash with the Commanders. Washington has been rather poor against the run in 2024, allowing 139.6 yards per tilt on the ground, which is 25th in the NFL. Washington has also yielded eight rushing touchdowns, which is tied for 18th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Tyrone Tracy has received 36 carries over the last two games for the Giants, parlaying those opportunities into over 200 yards rushing in the process. Tracy has usurped veteran Devin Singletary as the lead back, though the latter still rushed for 33 yards on seven carries in the last game for the G-Men. Still, Tracy will command the most touches out of the backfield in Week 10 in an extremely favorable matchup versus a struggling Carolina defense. The Panthers have allowed the most rushing yards and rushing touchdowns in the NFL to date.
outlooksByWeek.12: Tyrone Tracy has rushed for at least 100 yards and a touchdown in two of the last three games for the Giants. Unfortunately, Tracy lost a crucial fumble before the bye which ultimately cost the Giants the game versus the Panthers. Still, Tracy is averaging 5.1 yards per carry and figures to get the majority of the workload in Week 12 versus the Bucs as the Giants look to the future. Tommy DeVito will line up under center in place of the much-maligned Daniel Jones, and New York figures to lean heavily on the running game to support Tommy Cutlets. However, the Bucs have a decent run defense, allowing 125.2 yards per tilt on the ground, which is 16th in the league. Tampa Bay has also allowed just nine rushing scores in 2024, which is tied for 13th in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.13: Tyrone Tracy gained at least 65 scrimmage yards for the sixth-time in seven contests for the Giants. Tracy rushed for 42 yards and added 28 receiving yards in the 30-7 loss to the Bucs. On the downside, Tracy lost a crucial fumble for the second-straight game, and Devin Singletary also scavenged a one-yard touchdown plunge from the rookie. Given his recent fumbling issues as well as the struggles of the New York offense regardless of who lines up under center, perhaps expectations should be tempered for Tracy in Week 13. However, he will have a juicy matchup versus a Dallas defense that has been dreadful against the run in 2024. Dallas is allowing 150.5 rushing yards per tilt, which is 31st in the NFL. In addition, Dallas has allowed 19 rushing scores, which is dead last in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: The Giants chose Tracy in the fifth round of April's draft. He shined in his one season as a running back at Purdue after several seasons as a wide receiver in Iowa's troubling offense. Of course, the Giants signed former competent Texans/Bills veteran Devin Singletary in March, and he figures to handle the bulk of the work, but Singletary has never caught more than 40 passes or tallied 300 receiving yards in a season. Tracy may become the third-down back, but this still isn't a strong offense, so don't expect more than RB5 production.

outlooksByWeek.1: Najee Harris will begin the final season of his rookie contract with a Week 1 matchup against Atlanta. He should lead the Steelers in carries, and he posted his most efficient season on the ground in 2023, averaging 4.1 yards per carry while gaining at least 20 yards on eight separate attempts. On the other hand, Jaylen Warren has cut into Harris' receiving work significantly, dinging his value in PPR formats. It won't be an easy start to the season for Harris either, as the Falcons allowed only five touchdowns on the ground last campaign.
outlooksByWeek.2: Najee Harris was expected to split carries with Jaylen Warren out of the Pittsburgh backfield, but he instead racked up an impressive 20 carries in Week 1. His efficiency was less noteworthy as he averaged only 3.5 yards per attempt, with the end result being an empty 70 yards. Heading into a Week 2 matchup against Denver, Harris might see his touch total dip as Warren presumably gets healthier with additional time to recover from a hamstring injury. However, Pittsburgh is likely to continue to lean on its ground game, so Harris should maintain enough volume to be fantasy relevant.
outlooksByWeek.3: Najee Harris has served as the Steelers' unquestioned lead back through two weeks, racking up 37 carries and 39 total touches. The offense has been one-dimensional due to a limited pass offense, leading stacked boxes and limited rushing room for Harris and just a 3.8-yard per attempt mark. Jaylen Warren gathered an increase in workload in Week 2, so Harris could see his carry total shrink as the season progresses. However, he should still have considerable volume in Week 3 against the Chargers, who have been stout against the run early in the campaign.
outlooksByWeek.4: Najee Harris has shouldered a heavy workload in each of Pittsburgh's three games, tallying no fewer than 17 carries in a contest. That hasn't translated to much fantasy production, however, as he has yet to find the end zone and has only one carry inside the five-yard line for the season. Harris was spotted in a sling following the Steelers' Week 3 win over the Chargers, but there's no indication that he is in danger of missing a Week 4 matchup against the Colts. Assuming his health checks out, Harris should be a decent RB2 option, as the Colts have allowed both Joe Mixon and Josh Jacobs to top 150 yards on the ground early on this season.
outlooksByWeek.5: Najee Harris was concerningly outplayed by Cordarrelle Patterson in the Steelers backfield to begin a Week 4 matchup against the Colts. However, Harris continues to see strong volume, recording at least 16 touches in every game this season. That keeps him in fantasy consideration as an RB2/FLEX option, particularly because the Cowboys have allowed at least 18 PPR fantasy points to the opposing lead back in three of four games this season.
outlooksByWeek.6: Najee Harris operated as Pittsburgh's lead back by default against Dallas, as both Cordarrelle Patterson (ankle) and Jaylen Warren (knee) were sidelined. However, it was another poor performance, as he averaged just 3.0 yards per carry and has now averaged more than 4.0 yards per attempt in just one game this season. The good news is that he has salvaged his last two games with good efforts as a pass catcher, but career history suggests that won't be sustainable. If the Steelers' backfield remains depleted, Harris is a passable RB2 option in Week 6 against a Raiders defense that has allowed the second-most yards per carry in the league. If either of Warren and Patterson can return, it wouldn't be a surprise to see Harris lose work, so his fantasy viability will be dictated by the injury report.
outlooksByWeek.7: Najee Harris' volume has stabilized around 16 touches from Week 4 to Week 6 in the Pittsburgh offense. However, he displayed some surprising explosiveness in Week 6 against the Raiders, recording two rushes of at least 20 yards -- matching his total from the first five games of the season. Harris' volume may dip as the season wears on and Jaylen Warren returns from an injury-plagued start to the season, but Harris should remain the lead back in Week 7 against the Jets. Harris is a reasonable starting flex option, with the chance to be a low-end RB2.
outlooksByWeek.8: Najee Harris has lacked efficiency for much of his career, though he's now topped 100 rushing yards in each of his last two games while averaging 5.9 yards per carry. Russell Wilson brought balance to the Pittsburgh offense in Week 7, leading the Jets to put eight defenders in the box on an extremely low 4.8% of snaps. The threat of the deep ball should continue to benefit Harris in a Week 8 matchup against the Giants, who have allowed the second-most points per game to opposing running backs this season. Consider Harris a solid RB2.
outlooksByWeek.10: Najee Harris is in the midst of arguably the most effective stretch of his career, topping 100 rushing yards in the three games heading into the Steelers' Week 9 bye, averaging 6.0 yards per carry in that span. Harris remains relatively uninvolved as a receiver, preventing him from joining the elite options at the position, but he should be considered a solid RB2 option in Pittsburgh's Week 10 matchup against the Commanders. Washington has typically forced opposing offenses into relatively pass-heavy game scripts, which would limit Harris' volume, but it has also allowed 5.23 yards per carry -- the highest mark in the league.
outlooksByWeek.11: Week 10 marked the end of arguably the most efficient stretch of Najee Harris' career, as was bottled up for only 2.5 yards per carry. However, he still punched in a score and saw 21 carries to lead the Pittsburgh backfield. While his volume will remain safe, Harris could struggle to find running room in a Week 11 matchup against the Ravens, who have allowed only 3.23 yards per carry -- the second-lowest mark in the league. He's a strong FLEX option with the upside to perform as an RB2.
outlooksByWeek.12: Najee Harris continues to dominate work out of the Pittsburgh backfield, having earned at least 20 touches in each of his last four games. His efficiency has slipped in the last two, when he's averaged only two yards per carry. However, he has a touchdown and four receptions in those two contests, respectively, keeping him in range as a strong fantasy starter. A Week 12 matchup against the Browns will likely mean more of the same, as the Browns have allowed the seventh-fewest PPR fantasy points to opposing running backs this season. Consider Harris an RB2.
outlooksByWeek.13: Najee Harris logged a season-low 40% snap rate in Pittsburgh's Week 12 loss to the Browns, and he only narrowly led the team's backfield in carries. Game flow likely played a part in his suppressed performance as the Steelers were chasing points for much of the game, but Harris' lack of efficiency is concerning, particularly with Jaylen Warren getting healthy. Across his last three games, Harris has averaged just 2.9 yards per attempt. He's a risky RB2 in Week 13 against the Bengals, though Cincinnati has allowed 11 rushing touchdowns this season -- tied for fifth-most in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: A true volume grinder, Harris returns to Pittsburgh for his fourth season as the primary runner on early downs. Harris has totaled at least 255 carries and 1,000 rush yards for three straight seasons. However, Harris dipped to 11.4 fantasy points per game last season (RB26), and his receving totals continue to decline (career-low 29 receptions in 2023). A run-heavy approach from new offensive coordinator Arthur Smith is a bonus here, but with the expanding role for Jaylen Warren in the Steelers' backfield, Harris should be targeted as lower-tier flex only.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jauan Jennings enters Week 1 as the third wide receiver on the 49ers depth chart. The 49ers used three wide receiver personnel in under 40-percent of snaps last season, and he'll have a difficult task earning targets while sharing the field with Brandon Aiyuk and Deebo Samuel. The 49ers receivers also have an unappealing matchup against a talented Jets pass defense that allowed the third fewest passing yards per game in 2023. Jennings is a very difficult fantasy option to trust this weekend, and he likely needs an injury to Samuel or Aiyuk to see a major role in this offense.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jauan Jennings surprisingly led the 49ers in receiving yards in their season opener, catching all five of his targets for 64 yards. While it's promising to see Jennings play this efficiently, it will be difficult to sustain this type of output, as he played under half of the 49ers offensive snaps and has to compete with the likes of Brandon Aiyuk, Deebo Samuel, and George Kittle for targets. In Week 2, San Francisco goes up against a Minnesota passing defense that is coming off of a successful first week, holding the Giants to just 186 receiving yards. The Giants are not a very good offense, however, and the Vikings allowed the 10th most receiving yards in the league last season.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jauan Jennings caught two of his four targets over the weekend, totaling 37 receiving yards. Jennings is set to move up the depth chart in the short term, with Deebo Samuel reportedly set to miss the next couple of weeks after suffering a calf strain over the weekend. Jennings will see a boost in his offensive snaps and routes run, though he will still be the third receiving option behind Brandon Aiyuk and George Kittle. The 49ers go up against a struggling Rams defense in Week 3. They've allowed 483 receiving yards over their first two games, which is eighth most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jauan Jennings had the game of his career in the absence of several key 49ers offensive weapons, reeling in 11 of his 12 targets for 175 total receiving yards and three touchdowns. Jennings tied with Brandon Aiyuk for the most routes run over the weekend, and he played a major role with Christian McCaffrey, Deebo Samuel, and George Kittle all out with injuries. Jennings is unlikely to be this efficient moving forward, but if Samuel misses next weekend's game as expected due to his calf strain, he should continue to see volume in this offense. In Week 4, the 49ers host the Patriots, who have allowed 244 passing yards per game in 2024, fifth most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.6: Jauan Jennings had one reception on three targets for 13 yards in Week 5. Jennings played in just 36 of San Francisco's 64 snaps, and he is firmly behind Deebo Samuel and Brandon Aiyuk on the depth chart. Jennings additionally has to compete against Jordan Mason and George Kittle for touches, so it will be difficult for him to be a consistent fantasy option with his current workload. San Francisco plays Seattle in Week 6, and the Seahawks have allowed 183 passing yards per game in 2024, seventh best in the league.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jauan Jennings brought in three of his five targets for 27 yards in Week 6. Jennings played about half of San Francisco's offensive snaps, which aligns with his typical workload when Deebo Samuel and Brandon Aiyuk are healthy. Earning five targets on such a limited snap share is impressive, but it's difficult to maintain that sort of utilization on a weekly basis in a part-time role. In Week 7, Jennings and the 49ers face off against a Kansas City defense that has been average against the pass in 2024, allowing 217 yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.8: Jauan Jennings missed Week 7 due to a hip injury, and he is questionable for San Francisco's Week 8 game against the Cowboys. Coach Kyle Shanahan told the media this weekend that the team is hopeful to have Jennings available, reflecting some optimism for his recovery timeline. The 49ers need all the help they can get with Brandon Aiyuk out for the rest of the season, Deebo Samuel dealing with pneumonia, and Chris Conley dealing with an ankle sprain. If Jennings is active, he will likely play a key role in the passing game. Dallas has given up the second most points per game in 2024, and the unit has allowed 213 passing yards per game.
outlooksByWeek.10: Jauan Jennings missed two games heading into San Francisco's Week 9 bye with a hip injury. Coach Kyle Shanahan told the media that he expected Jennings to return for a Week 10 matchup against Tampa Bay. In his six starts this season, Jennings has earned at least four targets, and he'll compete with Ricky Pearsall for the number two spot on the wide receiver depth chart. The Buccaneers have allowed 255 passing yards per game, third most in the league.
outlooksByWeek.11: Jauan Jennings led the 49ers wide receivers in snaps, routes run, and targets in Week 10. Jennings caught seven of his 11 targets for 93 yards after missing San Francisco's previous two games with a hip injury. The 49ers are second in the league with 263 passing yards per game, so Jennings figures to be a solid fantasy option moving forward in this strong passing offense. In Week 11, San Francisco faces off against the Seahawks. Seattle's defense has allowed 218 passing yards per game this season, ranking 20th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.12: Jauan Jennings led the 49ers in targets and receiving yards in Week 11 for the second consecutive game. Jennings caught 10 of 11 targets for 91 yards and a touchdown, and he led San Francisco's wide receivers in snaps and routes run. Jennings has shined this season in the absence of Brandon Aiyuk, and he should continue to see plenty of targets from Brock Purdy in Week 12 when the 49ers face off against Green Bay. The Packers have allowed 208 passing yards per game this season, which ranks 13th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.13: Jauan Jennings caught five of seven targets for 40 yards in Week 12. Jennings' production suffered in comparison to his recent performances due to Brandon Allen starting for the injured Brock Purdy. His playing time was still excellent, and Jennings played most of San Francisco's offensive snaps while leading the team in targets. In Week 13, San Francisco faces off against the Bills. Buffalo's passing defense allows 210 yards per game, which ranks 14th in the league.

outlooksByWeek.1: Justin Herbert is coming off the worst season of his NFL career, as he missed four games due to a finger injury and set career lows with a 65.1 percent completion percentage, 3.134 passing yards and just 20 passing touchdowns. Things aren't pointed in the right direction for 2024, either. Herbert battled a plantar fascia issue in training camp which threatens to limit his mobility, and the Chargers' switch to Jim Harbaugh as head coach and Greg Roman as offensive coordinator should bring a much more run-heavy approach, denying the quarterback the high volume he's accustomed to. Herbert figures to be under center in Week 1 despite the foot injury, but he'll be facing a Raiders defense that finished in the top half of the league last year in passing yards and passing TDs allowed.
outlooksByWeek.2: Justin Herbert didn't have much to do in the Chargers' season-opening win over the Raiders. as RB J.K. Dobbins and the Los Angeles defense controlled the game. Herbert's 26 pass attempts were his fewest in a game since he was a rookie in 2020, but that could be the new normal for him under Jim Harbaugh. The Chargers also likely want to minimize how much he needs to move around while he recovers from a foot issue, limiting his ability to contribute on the ground as well. Herbert's volume figures to be low again in Week 2 against a Panthers team that got blown out by the Saints in their opener.
