outlooksByWeek.3: Justin Herbert has led the Chargers to two straight wins under new head coach Jim Harbaugh, and while he's tossed three touchdowns against just one interception, he's thrown for under 150 yards in both games as the team adopts a run-heavy offensive philosophy. The Chargers also built comfortable leads in both games, so whether Herbert will see more passing volume in more competitive contests remains to be seen. The fifth-year quarterback came out of Sunday's win over the Panthers with a lower-leg injury, putting his status for Week 3 in question. If he is able to suit up, Herbert will face a Steelers defense that's allowed a league-low 56.8 QB rating through two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.4: Justin Herbert left a Week 3 loss to the Steelers early after aggravating his high-ankle sprain, continuing a bumpy beginning to the season for the fifth-year quarterback. He's completed 67.2% of his passes through three games with four touchdowns against only one interception, but his 6.2 yards per attempt would be a career low, and he's been limited to only 24 rushing yards. X-rays taken after the game were negative, indicating Herbert's injury didn't get any worse, but with both of the Chargers' starting offensive tackles also banged up, the team may err on the side of caution and hold him out for a Week 4 clash with Kansas City. In that case, Taylor Heinicke appears next in line to get the start after taking over for Herbert in Week 3, although the more mobile Easton Stick would also be an option.
outlooksByWeek.6: Justin Herbert played through an ankle injury for the early part of the Chargers' schedule, but the team's Week 5 bye may have given him a chance to get healthier. While he does have a respectable 64.8% completion rate and 5:1 TD:INT, his 6.4 yards per attempt is a career low. Young wideouts Ladd McConkey and Quentin Johnston have accounted for all five of those touchdowns, and Herbert's numbers could improve as they continue their development. He faces a stiff test in Week 6 against a Broncos defense that ranks fifth in the league with a 75.5 QB rating against.
outlooksByWeek.7: Justin Herbert showed signs of improvement in Week 6 following the Chargers' bye, throwing for over 200 yards for the first time and averaging a season-high 7.0 yards per attempt against a stingy Broncos secondary. The quarterback is still playing through an ankle injury, but he may be getting close to 100% healthy. The Chargers continue to lean heavily on J.K. Dobbins and their ground game, but with rookie wideout Ladd McConkey emerging as Herbert's top downfield target, there could be some upside in the team's passing attack as well. In Week 7, Herbert will face a much less fearsome Cardinals defense that ranks 31st in completion rate allowed.
outlooksByWeek.8: Justin Herbert posted season highs with 349 passing yards and 8.9 yards per attempt in Week 7, but he also failed to throw a touchdown for the first time all year as the Chargers lost for the third time in four games. The fifth-year quarterback's numbers are on the upswing as he gets healthier, and over two games since the team's bye he's completed 65.8% of his passes for an 8.0 YPA after managing a mark of just 6.4 through the first four weeks. Herbert's lack of an established No. 1 target could be holding him back, as none of Joshua Palmer, Ladd McConkey or Quentin Johnston have proven they can contribute consistently. Herbert will try to take advantage of a Week 8 clash with a reeling Saints defense that ranks second in QB rating against despite sitting 28th in passing yards per game allowed.
outlooksByWeek.9: Justin Herbert continues to get healthier and more productive. The fifth-year quarterback threw multiple touchdowns in Week 8 for the first time since Week 2, and even more encouragingly, he ran for a season-high 49 yards, a strong sign his ankle is just about 100%. Herbert also may have found his new No. 1 receiver, as rookie Ladd McConkey had a breakout performance in that Week 8 win over the Saints. Herbert could be ready to take advantage of a Week 9 clash with a Browns defense that's allowed 12.4 yards per reception this season, 30th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.10: Justin Herbert is getting back to his usual form. The Chargers' quarterback has thrown multiple TD passes in consecutive games for the first time this season, and his 10.4 YPA in Week 9 against the Browns was his high-water mark for 2024. Herbert's quickly building chemistry with young wideouts Quentin Johnston, who erupted for a 4-118-1 line against Cleveland, and Ladd McConkey, who delivered a 6-111-2 line in Week 8. Herbert faces a potentially tough test in Week 10 against a Titans defense that's given up the fewest passing yards in the league this year.
outlooksByWeek.11: Justin Herbert produced multiple touchdowns for the third straight game in a Week 10 win over the Titans, including his first rushing TD of the season. The fifth-year QB also set a season high with a 77.8% completion rate, and he appears to be completely over the ankle injury that hampered him to begin the year. He's also showing good chemistry with young wideouts Quentin Johnston and Ladd McConkey, as the duo has hauled in four of Herbert's last five TD passes. Herbert figures to be productive again in Week 11 as the Chargers face a Bengals defense that ranks 28th in fantasy points per game allowed to QBs.
outlooksByWeek.12: Justin Herbert continues to demonstrate that he's fully recovered from his early-season ankle injury. He ran for a season-high 65 yards in a Week 11 win over the Bengals, and he topped an 8.0 yards per attempt for the fifth straight game. Over that stretch, Herbert has delivered a 7:0 TD:INT with a 63.2% completion rate and 9.0 yards per attempt, a big improvement on his numbers prior to the Chargers' Week 4 bye. He figures to come through with another productive game in Week 12 against a Ravens defense that's given up the most passing yards in the league.
outlooksByWeek.13: Justin Herbert failed to throw a touchdown in Week 12, the first time since Week 7, but he compensated by running for his second TD in the last three games. The Chargers quarterback appears fully healthy, and over the last six contests he's posted an 8.5 yards per attempt and 7:0 TD:INT, although his 62.2% completion rate is less impressive. J.K. Dobbins also suffered a knee injury in that Week 12 loss to the Ravens, which could put more emphasis on the Chargers' passing attack if he's sidelined for a significant period, Herbert will face a Falcons defense in Week 13 that ranks dead last in the league in completion percentage allowed, and 26th in fantasy points per game allowed to QBs.

player.seasonOutlook: While Herbert is one of the league's most talented quarterbacks, he is saddled with starting for a Jim Harbaugh rebuild that's precariously thin on receiving talent. In the past three seasons, Herbert is third in passing yards per game (274.1), fourth among qualifiers in Total QBR (65.3) and he has averaged 19.1 fantasy points per game. That latter number placed eighth at the position, in large part because Herbert couldn't get things done behind a sputtering running game and with Mike Williams and Keenan Allen missing time due to injury in 2023. Allen and Williams are now elsewhere, and Harbaugh appears committed to a run-oriented offense. Herbert might struggle to deliver the fantasy goods, making him more of a matchup play for 2024.

outlooksByWeek.1: Calvin Ridley will make his Titans debut in a Week 1 road matchup against a Chicago defense that allowed the ninth-fewest yards to wide receivers last season but tied for the sixth-most touchdowns allowed to the position. After sitting out the 2022 season, Ridley returned to the NFL with 1,016 receiving yards for the Jaguars in 2023 before signing a four-year, $92 million contract with the Titans in March. Ridley is expected to be the top target for second-year QB Will Levis but figures to see a heavy dose of standout Bears cornerback Jaylon Johnson, especially if fellow Tennessee WR DeAndre Hopkins (knee) isn't 100 percent.
outlooksByWeek.2: Calvin Ridley accounted for 50 of Will Levis' 127 passing yards in Week 1, but Tennessee's prized free-agent acquisition will face elite Jets cornerbacks Sauce Gardner and DJ Reed in Week 2. Gardner and Reed helped the Jets limit wide receivers to the fewest yards in the league last season. Ridley's the clear No. 1 option in Tennessee's receiving corps with DeAndre Hopkins at less than full health due to a knee injury, but the Titans will likely try to beat the Jets primarily on the ground. Ridley has at least 50 yards in six of his last nine games after reaching that mark only three times in his first nine games back after being suspended for the 2022 season.
outlooksByWeek.3: Calvin Ridley has been the leading receiver in each of his first two games with the Titans, and he'll look to keep rolling in Week 3 against the Packers. He has 127 receiving yards and a TD through two games, plus another TD on the ground. Green Bay's secondary has big-name cornerback Jaire Alexander, but the Packers have allowed 323 yards and two TDs to WRs through two games, and Alexander seems to be a notch below Chicago's Jaylon Johnson and the Jets' Sauce Gardner, whom Ridley faced in Weeks 1 and 2. Ridley's early success has come despite the struggles of QB Will Levis, who has just 319 passing yards with a 2:3 TD:INT.
outlooksByWeek.4: Calvin Ridley will be looking to bounce back from a nine-yard Week 3 dud in Week 4 against a Dolphins secondary that ranks in the middle of the pack. After racking up 127 receiving yards and two total TDs through two games with the Titans, Ridley had just one catch in Week 3 against the Packers while DeAndre Hopkins broke out for 73 yards and a TD. Will Levis' struggles have made it difficult for Tennessee to sustain more than one fantasy-relevant WR at a time, but Ridley still slides in ahead of Hopkins in the WR2/3 range, and Hopkins' presence could take some of the attention of star Dolphins CB Jalen Ramsey away from Ridley.
outlooksByWeek.6: Calvin Ridley had just 14 receiving yards in Tennessee's last two games before a Week 5 bye, cooling off after a hot start that saw him post 127 receiving yards and two totals TDs through two weeks. The speedy wideout has a nice opportunity to get back on track in Week 6 against a Colts defense that's allowing 180.2 receiving yards per game to WRs. His floor is low as Ridley battles a healthy DeAndre Hopkins for targets from either Will Levis (shoulder) or Mason Rudolph, but Ridley's high ceiling against the leaky Colts secondary puts him on the fantasy WR2/WR3 borderline despite his recent struggles.
outlooksByWeek.7: Calvin Ridley failed to catch any of his eight targets in Week 6 against the Colts, marking his third consecutive game with no more than one catch. Getting back on track won't be easy for the struggling wideout in Week 7 against a Bills secondary that's limiting WRs to 132.3 receiving yards per game. DeAndre Hopkins has supplanted Ridley as the top option in Tennessee's passing game, leaving Ridley as a flex play at best in Week 7.
outlooksByWeek.8: Calvin Ridley's mired in an ugly four-game slump, having caught only five of 23 targets for 56 yards from Week 3 onward. A silver lining for the struggling wideout is that he collected a season-high nine targets from Mason Rudolph in Week 7 against the Bills, and his Week 8 opponent is a Detroit defense that's allowing a league-high 213.2 receiving yards per game to WRs. Whether it's Rudolph or Will Levis (shoulder) under center for the Titans in Week 8, Ridley is well positioned to bounce back against the generous Lions secondary and is a solid fantasy WR3, though fantasy managers can't be blamed for looking elsewhere after his recent string of disappointing outings, especially since Ridley's battling a foot injury.
outlooksByWeek.9: Calvin Ridley set season highs in targets (15), catches (10) and receiving yards (143) in Tennessee's Week 8 loss to the Lions. That productive outing came in the first game after the Titans traded DeAndre Hopkins to Kansas City, but Ridley caught only five of 23 targets for 56 yards over his previous four games. Ridley's a solid fantasy WR3 in Week 9 against the Patriots as the clear No. 1 option in Tennessee's passing game, regardless of whether Will Levis (shoulder) or Mason Rudolph is throwing him the ball. New England's defense has been more generous than league average to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.10: Calvin Ridley has bounced back with 216 receiving yards in Weeks 8 and 9 combined after a four-game slump. He's the clear No. 1 WR for the Titans now that DeAndre Hopkins is a Chief, which should give Ridley a high target floor regardless of whether Will Levis (shoulder) or Mason Rudolph starts at QB for Tennessee in Week 10 against the Chargers. Ridley will be a WR3 for fantasy purposes against a Chargers secondary that has allowed the fourth-fewest yards to WRs this season.
outlooksByWeek.11: Calvin Ridley has taken his game to another level since the departure of DeAndre Hopkins from Tennessee. In three subsequent games, Ridley has racked up 300 receiving yards and two TDs. Ridley should keep rolling in Week 11 against a Vikings secondary that's giving up 178 receiving yards per game to WRs, making Tennessee's top wideout a solid fantasy WR2.
outlooksByWeek.12: Calvin Ridley has 358 receiving yards and two TDs in four games since the Titans traded away DeAndre Hopkins. The surging wideout will be a fantasy WR2 in Week 12 against a Texans secondary that's tied for the most TDs allowed to WRs (16) and is giving up 152.8 receiving yards per game to the position. QB Will Levis accumulated a season-high 295 passing yards against the Vikings in Week 11, so Tennessee's entire passing game is trending in the right direction.
outlooksByWeek.13: Calvin Ridley is averaging 90.2 receiving yards in five games since the Titans traded away DeAndre Hopkins prior to Week 8. Ridley has led the team in receiving yards in four of those five games, and he's poised to keep rolling in Week 13 against a Commanders defense that's allowing 139.3 receiving yards per game to WRs. With Will Levis looking more competent under center in recent weeks, Ridley's a rock-solid fantasy WR2 for Week 13.

player.seasonOutlook: Joining the Titans in free agency via a rich new pact was a bit surprising, and also very interesting. Ridley's return to NFL action in 2023 resulted in a somewhat volatile season in Jacksonville. He had seven games with at least 83 receiving yards and nine with 40 yards or fewer. A sluggish catch rate of 55.9% (lowest among the top 40 in targets) was a key culprit. The Titans paid Ridley handsomely to help open the downfield offense next to DeAndre Hopkins, while aiding Will Levis' progression as a professional passer. Much like last season, a blend of volume and variance is likely the story with Ridley. There will be valleys, but also impressive peaks. Taking on Ridley in the middle rounds on the fringes of WR2 and WR3 pricing could prove rewarding.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jakobi Meyers scored a career-high eight receiving touchdowns in 2023, but otherwise his numbers in his first season with the Raiders were right in line with his production his final two years with the Patriots. The undrafted NC State product has carved out a respectable NFL career for himself, but he has a tall task in 2024 to haul in his usual 800-plus yards and 60-70 receptions. The Las Vegas offense figures to be more run-focused with Gardner Minshew providing some stability, but not more upside, as the starting quarterback, and Meyers' role on intermediate routes could be threatened by the team's recent investments at tight end, where 2024 first-round pick Brock Bowers joins 2023 second-round pick Michael Mayer. Meyers will try to take advantage of a Week 1 matchup against a Chargers secondary that finished in the bottom four in receiving touchdowns allowed and yards per target allowed to wideouts last year.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jakobi Meyers only gathered only three Week 1 targets in the Raiders' season-opening loss to the Chargers, but he caught all three for a team-high 61 receiving yards. The veteran wideout put up comparable production to both WR Davante Adams and rookie TE Brock Bowers, and new QB Gardner Minshew could focus his attention on those three for the most part in 2024, with Meyers being the possession receiver of the trio. A 33-yard gain boosted his average in Week 1, but Meyers hasn't topped 9.0 yards per target in his any of his prior five NFL seasons. He faces a tough matchup in Week 2 against a Ravens secondary that was one of the stingiest in the league in 2023, although it did allow some big plays to wideouts Rashee Rice and Xavier Worthy in a loss to Kansas City last week.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jakobi Meyers has collected steady volume as a secondary option in the Raiders' passing game through two games, catching seven of eight targets for 90 yards. The veteran wideout appears to have a solid floor, but his ceiling could be limited with Davante Adams and rookie tight end Brock Bowers being the most dangerous options at QB Gardner Minshew's disposal. Meyers did score a career-high eight touchdowns in 2023, but he's collected only one red-zone target so far this season, usage which will make it difficult to repeat that scoring production. He may not garner many looks in Week 3 against a Panthers secondary that teams haven't needed to throw much against so far, and which has given up only 15 receptions to WRs through two weeks, tied for the lowest figure in the league.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jakobi Meyers produced his best numbers of the season Week 3, catching seven of nine targets for 62 yards and a touchdown. The veteran wideout has been a clear secondary option behind Davante Adams, logging 17 targets to Adams' 27, but Meyers has still delivered a respectable 14-152-1 line. In Week 4 against the Browns, he will get the chance to be the No. 1 WR option as Adams is out with a hamstring injury. The Raiders' offense has struggled overall, though, with poor offensive line play sabotaging the running game. Quarterback Gardner Minshew was benched late in Week 3 in favor of Aidan O'Connell, but Meyers' usage likely wouldn't change much based on who is under center in Week 4 against a Browns secondary that hasn't been as stingy as usual and has given up three TDs to WRs through three games.
outlooksByWeek.5: Jakobi Meyers benefitted from the absence of Davante Adams in Week 4, gathering a season-high 10 targets, but he was able to turn them into only five catches for 49 yards. Meyers has had a tepid start to the season for the Raiders, but his 19-201-1 line on 27 targets through four games still puts him on pace for his fourth straight season with more than 800 receiving yards. Adams' hamstring strain could sideline him again in Week 5 against the Broncos, but that might not be to Meyers' advantage. Without Adams on the field, Meyers would get more attention from shutdown corner Patrick Surtain, and Denver's secondary overall has given up the fourth-fewest receiving yards in the league to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.6: Jakobi Meyers has gathered at least nine targets in three straight games, taking advantage of the absence of Davante Adams due to a hamstring injury. Meyers' 18-183-1 line on 28 total targets during that time could become his new normal, as Adams is now on the trade block and may not play again for the Raiders. The team's passing game is set for even more changes too, as Aidan O'Connell is replacing Gardner Minshew under center. Meyers is now dealing with an ankle injury of his own, but if he suits up in Week 6, he will try to work through the chaos against a Steelers secondary that ranks in the top half of the league in catches and touchdowns allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jakobi Meyers missed a Week 6 loss to the Steelers due to an ankle injury, but once he gets healthy, he figures to be the Raiders' new No. 1 wideout. Davante Adams was dealt to the Jets this week, leaving Meyers as the only veteran on an otherwise very young receiving corp. He was already garnering increased volume, posting an 18-183-1 line on 28 targets from Week 3 to 5, but those came with Gardner Minshew as the starting quarterback, and Aidan O'Connell took the reins of the offense in Week 6. If Meyers returns to the lineup in Week 7, O'Connell could lean on him heavily against a Rams secondary that ranks in the top seven in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs, but largely because the defense has been more vulnerable on the ground than through the air.
outlooksByWeek.8: Jakobi Meyers has missed the last two games with an ankle injury, but when he is able to return he figures to be the Raiders' clear No. 1 wide receiver. Davante Adams was traded to the Jets while he was sidelined, and second-year player Tre Tucker has yet to make a big impact in a larger offensive role. Meyers' primary competition for targets is likely to come from rookie tight end Brock Bowers, but the team's switch at quarterback back to Gardner Minshew isn't likely to move the needle much either way. If Meyers can suit up in Week 8, he'll be facing a Kansas City secondary that has given up the fewest receiving yards in the league to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.9: Jakobi Meyers returned from a two-game absence in Week 8 and posted solid numbers, catching six of seven targets for 52 yards and a touchdown in a loss to Kansas City. The veteran has Gardner Minshew under center once again and is the Raiders' top wideout with Davante Adams gone, although the team's true No. 1 pass-catcher is rookie tight end Brock Bowers. Meyers has been dependable when healthy though, posting a 24-235-2 line on 35 targets over his last four games. He'll take on a Bengals secondary in Week 9 that ranks 23rd in receptions allowed to WRs.
outlooksByWeek.11: Jakobi Meyers topped the century mark for the first time as a Raider in Week 9, prior to the team's bye. The veteran wideout hauled in eight of 11 targets for 105 yards, his best performance since 2022 with the Patriots, and that kind of volume could become the norm for him as Las Vegas' No. 1 receiver. Meyers' only real competition for looks is rookie tight end Brock Bowers, as the Raiders' WR depth chart has become very thin. Meyers faces a tough test in Week 11 against a Dolphins secondary that ranks in the top eight in receiving yards and TDs allowed to wide receivers.
outlooksByWeek.12: Jakobi Meyers struggled to make a splash in a Week 11 loss to the Dolphins, catching four of six targets for 28 yards. He did add 20 rushing yards on his only carry. Meyers is the top wide receiver on the Raiders' depth chart, but he appears to be quarterback Gardner Minshew's second read behind rookie tight end Brock Bowers, limiting his upside. Meyers will likely provide more of a floor than a ceiling in Week 12 against a Broncos secondary that ranks in the middle of the pack in catches and receiving yards allowed to WRs, but which has given up only six touchdowns to the position, the second-lowest total in the league.
outlooksByWeek.13: Jakobi Meyers is coming off his best performance of the season, catching 10 of 15 targets for 121 yards in a Week 12 loss to the Broncos. It's the second time in his last three games he's topped the century mark, but those numbers came with Gardner Minshew under center for the Raiders. With Minshew out for the rest of the year due to a broken collarbone, Meyers will be working with either Aidan O'Connell or Desmond Ridder, potentially affecting his volume and effectiveness. Regardless of who's getting him the ball, Meyers will face a Kansas City secondary in Week 13 that ranks sixth in the league in receiving yards allowed to WRs.

player.seasonOutlook: Meyers' familiarity with Josh McDaniels' system afforded him a hot start to 2023. He was 20th among WRs through eight weeks with 108.4 fantasy points. After the Raiders dispatched McDaniels, Meyers' production dipped, as he averaged 3.3 fewer points and 2.6 fewer targets per game from that point forward. Ultimately, Meyers finished 24th in fantasy production among wide receivers, a good enough stat line to earn him No. 2 target status again in the Raiders' 2024 offense and a fantasy flex valuation. The team's iffy quarterback situation, however, might mean the second-half version is the more likely one we'll see this year.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jaylen Warren broke out in 2023 with the Steelers and will look to replicate his results in 2024 starting with a Week 1 matchup against Atlanta. He suffered an injury scare when he strained his hamstring in preseason action, but Warren has since returned to practice and is planning to suit up to open the campaign. Warren will likely still lag behind Najee Harris in rushing attempts, but he is a strong contributor as a receiver and is also a solid change of pace to Harris on the ground. It won't be an easy matchup for either back in Week 1, as the Falcons allowed only five rushing touchdowns for the entire 2023 campaign.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jaylen Warren was surprisingly uninvolved in the Pittsburgh offense in Week 1, earning only two carries and two receptions. He may have been limited by a calf injury that he sustained midway through the preseason, as he was on the field for only 19 offensive snaps (29 percent). While he has had additional time to recover, he remains a risky start in Week 2 against Denver. Najee Harris is capable of handling a full workload out of the backfield, so the Steelers may continue to limit Warren's reps.
outlooksByWeek.3: Jaylen Warren appears to be progressing from a hamstring injury, as he saw his offensive snap count tick up from 19 to 26 from Week 1 to Week 2. He still worked behind Najee Harris, being out touched 18-11, though that could change if Warren can regain his efficiency from 2023. For now, he should be considered the backup to Harris as the Steelers head into a Week 3 matchup against the Chargers stout the run defense, rendering Warren as a risky start until he proves capable of handling more volume.
outlooksByWeek.4: Jaylen Warren was slowed by a hamstring injury in the preseason and never seemed to get fully healthy as he sought to secure a role in the Pittsburgh backfield. Heading out of a Week 3 win over the Colts, he's now set for an MRI on his knee. The damage is unclear for the time being, but it's difficult to trust Warren heading into a Week 4 matchup against the Colts until he can string together consecutive healthy weeks.
outlooksByWeek.5: Jaylen Warren will not play Week 5 against the Cowboys because of a knee injury. Warren has had a tough time staying healthy to begin the season. Although Week 4 was his first missed game, he was limited earlier in the campaign by a hamstring issue only to ultimately be sidelined by  the injury. Cordarrelle Patterson is also out, leaving Aaron Shampklin to back up Najee Harris on Sunday.
outlooksByWeek.6: Jaylen Warren's frustrating season continued as he missed Pittsburgh's Week 5 matchup against the Cowboys with a knee injury. He failed to practice in any capacity, also placing his availability into question for a Week 6 contest against Las Vegas. Once Warren returns to full health, he has a strong case to have at least an even split in the backfield with Najee Harris due to the latter's inefficiency, making him a reasonable stash candidate.
outlooksByWeek.7: Jaylen Warren returned from a two-game absence caused by a knee injury to earn nine touches in Pittsburgh's Week 6 win, though he managed only a total of 19 yards from scrimmage. He should keep a similar role in a Week 7 matchup against the Jets, who have been a mediocre defense against opposing running backs this season. Warren could see more work as the season progresses if Najee Harris remains inefficient, but it's difficult to trust him in the short term.
outlooksByWeek.8: Jaylen Warren appears to be healthy for the first time this season, as he logged season highs in both snap rate (50%) and touches (14) in Week 7 against the Jets. He's still working behind a suddenly efficient Najee Harris, leaving Warren as the change-of-pace back and reliant upon game flow. Even in a favorable Week 8 matchup against the Giants, it's difficult to trust Warren as a starting option.
outlooksByWeek.10: Jaylen Warren battled various lower-body injuries to begin the season but looked to be relatively healthy heading into Pittsburgh's Week 9 bye as he logged 14 and 11 touches in the team's prior two games. Coming off of the week of rest, Warren should continue to work as the change-of-pace back behind Najee Harris in a run-heavy offense. Warren has some FLEX appeal in a Week 10 matchup against the Commanders, a defensive unit that has allowed 5.23 yards per carry to opposing backs -- the highest mark in the league.
outlooksByWeek.11: Jaylen Warren has seen his role grow in the Pittsburgh offense as he's finally recovered from a couple of early-season lower-body injuries. While he's still been out-paced by Najee Harris, Warren has double-digit touches in three consecutive games while posting a season-best 95 yards from scrimmage in Week 10. A Week 11 matchup against the Ravens has the potential to stall his progress, as they are one of the stingier defensive units against opposing running backs, but Warren has worked himself into the FLEX conversation with his recent performances.
outlooksByWeek.12: Jaylen Warren has consistent involvement in the Pittsburgh offense, recording 16 and 13 touches in the last two games. He has yet to find the end zone and has topped 50 rushing yards in only one contest, making him more valuable to the Steelers than fantasy managers. Warren will head into a Week 12 matchup against the Browns, a defensive unit that has allowed the seventh-fewest PPR points per game to opposing running backs. He's a FLEX option in deeper leagues.
outlooksByWeek.13: Jaylen Warren has provided a strong change-of-pace presence out of the Pittsburgh backfield, as he's topped 40 rushing yards in five consecutive games while averaging 4.6 yards per attempt. He also offers a strong floor with his work as a pass catcher, managing at least three receptions in half of his last six games. The next question is whether he can overtake Najee Harris as the lead back down the stretch. As for a Week 13 matchup against Cincinnati, Warren is a palatable FLEX option due to his consistent work as a receiver.

player.seasonOutlook: Now entering his third pro season, Warren emerged as a playmaking talent with the Steelers in 2023, posting career highs across the board in rushing and receving. Warren posted a run of 10 or more yards on 15.5% of his carries, while producing double-digit fantasy points in 10 of 15 games played. He's an explosive mover, with perimeter juice and the open-field vision to produce as a screen target (18 receptions, 114 yards on screens last season). While Warren will share backfield touches with Najee Harris, he brings more fantasy upside as a dual-threat back under new offensive coordinator Arthur Smith. Target Warren as a high-end flex, with RB2 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cameron Dicker built on his strong finish to the 2022 campaign last season, connecting on all 35 of his extra point tries and missing only two field goals all year, both from 50 yards or more. The Texas product's 31 made FGs ranked in the top 10 in the NFL, thanks in part to an inefficient Chargers offense that finished in the bottom half of the league in red-zone touchdowns. That efficiency should change in 2024 as new head coach Jim Harbaugh and new offensive coordinator Greg Roman transition to a run-heavy scheme, forcing the Chargers' kicker to settle for more PATs rather than FGs. Dicker lines up to face a Raiders team in Week 1 that ranked a surprising ninth in the league last season at 19.5 points per game allowed.
outlooksByWeek.2: Cameron Dicker was perfect in Week 1's win over the Raiders, connecting on all three of his field-goal attempts and his only extra-point try. Dicker missed only two kicks in total in 2023, and his favorable 2024 schedule includes 11 games in indoor stadiums, so poor conditions will rarely be a factor. The Chargers' shift to a run-heavy offense under Jim Harbaugh could also lead to more opportunities for Dicker if QB Justin Herbert can't get the team into the end zone consistently. Dicker could be very busy in Week 2 against a Panthers team that gave up nine straight scoring drives against the Saints last week before finally getting a stop.
outlooksByWeek.3: Cameron Dicker missed his first kick of the season in Week 2, an extra point, but he's 5-for-5 on field-goal attempts through two Chargers wins. The team's run-heavy offense has been effective for the most part but has gone just 3-for-6 in the red zone in scoring TDs, leaving plenty of points on the table for Dicker to cash in. After a strong campaign in 2023, he appears to have solved the franchise's long-time kicking woes. Dicker may need to take advantage of every opportunity in Week 3 against a Steelers team that's allowed just 8.0 points per game through two weeks.
outlooksByWeek.4: Cameron Dicker didn't garner many opportunities in a Week 3 loss to the Steelers, but he converted his only field-goal attempt and his only PAT. The third-year kicker has a career 95.1% success rate on FGs and has only missed one of his 64 career extra-point tries, but the Chargers' low-ceiling, run-first offense will require Dicker to be nearly perfect and not leave points on the table. That offense faces additional obstacles to productivity in Week 4 against Kansas City, as Justin Herbert has been playing through a high-ankle sprain he aggravated in Week 3, and Los Angeles is dealing with multiple injuries along the offensive line. Dicker may incur low volume again in Week 4, even against a Kansas City team allowing a mediocre 20.7 points per game.
outlooksByWeek.6: Cameron Dicker has seen modest volume through the Chargers' first four games. The third-year kicker has only eight field-goal attempts and six extra-point tries, missing one of each, and the team's early offensive struggles have limited his opportunities. Part of the issue has been that Justin Herbert was playing through an ankle injury, but if he was able to use the team's Week 5 bye to get healthier, it could lift everyone's production. including Dicker's. He faces a stingy opponent in Week 6, as the Broncos are tied for second in the NFL with the Steelers at 14.6 points per game allowed.
outlooksByWeek.7: Cameron Dicker tied his season high with three made field goals in Week 6, en route to a season-high 11 points. The modest bump in production comes after the Chargers' Week 5 bye, and the time off may have allowed quarterback Justin Herbert to get healthier. If Herbert does begin to play closer to his capabilities, it should provide a boost to the entire offense, including Dicker. The Kicker will face a Cardinals team in Week 7 that's given up 27.2 points per game this season, tied for 27th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.8: Cameron Dicker's opportunities are increasing since the Chargers' Week 5 bye, and he's converted all eight of his field-goal attempts over the last two games. He's only gotten two extra-point tries, drilling them both, but offensive inefficiency generally works in a kicker's favor. The Chargers are 30th in the league in red-zone success rate, although as Justin Herbert gets heathier and returns to form, that rate should rise. Dicker will look to exploit a Week 8 clash with a Saints team that has given up the most FG attempts in the league while being tied for 27th in points per game allowed.
outlooksByWeek.9: Cameron Dicker has been busy since the Chargers' Week 5 bye, converting all 10 of his field-goal attempts and four of his five extra-point tries. Dicker has attempted multiple field goals in six of seven games this season, but with Justin Herbert rounding into form, the ceiling for the team's offense is rising. That could mean more PATs, but Dicker is already on pace to top the 33 field-goal tries he logged in 2023. He should enjoy solid volume in Week 9 against a Browns team that's given up at least 20 points in six straight games.
outlooksByWeek.10: Cameron Dicker failed to kick a field goal in Week 9 for the first time all season, missing his only attempt while going 3-for-4 on extra-point tries. It was the first time in his career he'd missed multiple kicks in the same game, and after being perfect on PATs coming into 2024, Dicker is only 12-for-15 on extra points this season. With Justin Herbert fully healthy though, the Chargers' offense figures to be more efficient in the second half, which should increase Dicker's opportunities. In Week 10 he'll take on a Titans squad that's coughed up 26.6 points per game this year, 27th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.11: Cameron Dicker's steady opportunities continue as the Chargers' offense improves. Over five games since the team's Week 5 bye, he's converted 12 of 13 field-goal attempts and 10 of 12 extra points, and he's attempted multiple FG in seven of nine games this season. With QB Justin Herbert seemingly now fully healthy, points could come easier for the Chargers, even if the offense remains run heavy. Dicker figures to be busy in Week 11 against a Bengals surrendering 26.2 points per game this year, 26th in the league.
outlooksByWeek.12: Cameron Dicker stayed busy in Week 11, converting multiple field goals for the fifth time in the last six games and booting a season-high four PATs. The third-year kicker's opportunities have increased as quarterback Justin Herbert returned to 100% health, and the Chargers' offense could only get better over the final weeks of the campaign. Dicker hasn't been quite as reliable as he was in 2023 however, missing three of 22 extra-point tries and two of 23 FG attempts, including his first career miss from less than 50 yards. He should enjoy significant volume again in Week 12 against a Ravens team that sits in the bottom 10 in points per game allowed and total FG attempts allowed.
outlooksByWeek.13: Cameron Dicker has been one of the most consistent kickers in the league since the Chargers' Week 5 bye. Over the last seven games, he's booted multiple field goals six times and multiple extra points on six occasions, going 17-for-18 on FGs and 16-for-18 on PATs. Dicker is tied for fifth in the league with 93 points, and with Justin Herbert healthy he could continue to see big volume. He should be busy in Week 13 against a Falcons team that's given up 24.9 points per game, 25th in the league.

player.seasonOutlook: Dicker has been quite a find for the Chargers, who scooped him up off waivers in mid-2022. In 28 games, he has converted all but three field goal attempts, including a perfect 45-for-45 on kicks shorter than 50 yards, and he hasn't missed any of his 59 extra-point attempts. Dicker was seventh in total fantasy points and ninth in top-10 weekly performances in 2023. He'll serve in the same capacity in 2024, for a run-heavy Chargers offense that might find itself in an advantageous number of field goal situations. Dicker's offense might lead to some weekly scoring inconsistency, but he's a solid pick once the kickers from higher-powered offenses are off the board.
